cff-version: 1.2.0
title: "vocal-helper: an async producer-consumer speech pipeline"
message: >-
  If you use this software in a publication, please cite it as below.
type: software
authors:
  - given-names: Warith
    family-names: HARCHAOUI
    email: warith@deraison.ai
    orcid: "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-3487-7134"
    affiliation: "Deraison AI"
repository-code: "https://github.com/warith-harchaoui/vocal-helper"
url: "https://github.com/warith-harchaoui/vocal-helper"
abstract: >-
  vocal-helper turns a live PCM audio stream (or a URL / WAV file) into
  diarised, transcribed utterances and, optionally, a rolling LLM summary.
  The pipeline chains a Silero VAD, an online cosine-clustering diarizer
  built on pyannote/embedding (or NVIDIA TitaNet via NeMo), a whisper.cpp
  turbo ASR (large-v3-turbo-q5_0), and an Ollama-hosted Gemma analyst.
  Every stage is an async coroutine wired by bounded asyncio queues, so
  back-pressure and shutdown cascade cleanly through the chain. The
  default operating points (join threshold 0.30 for the diarizer, 60 s
  rolling window for the analyst, TitaNet as the embedding backend) are
  each backed by a reproducible sweep under ``studies/`` on the AMI
  meeting corpus.
keywords:
  - "speech recognition"
  - "speaker diarization"
  - "voice activity detection"
  - "whisper"
  - "pyannote"
  - "silero"
  - "streaming"
  - "producer-consumer"
  - "asyncio"
  - "ollama"
  - "gemma"
